# Duplicate time to treatment variable as x for fixest indicator binning
df$x <- df$tt

# Define fixest variable macros
setFixest_fml(
  ..ds = ~i(tt, ref = -1, bin = .("-6" = ~x <= -6, "5" = ~x >= 5)),
  ..controls = ~month_income + month_spend + accounts_active,
  ..fe = ~user_id + ym,
  ..mvfe = ~mvsw(user_id, ym)
)

Expectation

When estimating model with different event windows, we’d not expect estimates for period in both models to change.

m1 <- feols(dspend ~ i(tt, ref = -1, bin = .("-6" = ~x <= -6, "5" = ~x >= 5)) + ..controls, df)
m2 <- feols(dspend ~ i(tt, ref = -1, bin = .("-3" = ~x <= -3, "5" = ~x >= 5)) + ..controls, df)
iplot(list(m1, m2))

Anomalie

However, above models don’t include fixed effects, which we need. Once we do that, however, we get the following:

What’s going on here?

Hypothesis: it’s a sample issue

We might think that the two models are baseed on different samples, but this is not the case. We can see this by estimating only effects for periods we have ensured in sample selection that each user has data for it. We get the same issue.

m1 <- feols(dspend ~ i(tt, ref = -1, bin = .("-6" = ~x <= -6, "5" = ~x >= 5)) + ..controls | user_id + ym, df)
m2 <- feols(dspend ~ i(tt, ref = -1, bin = .("-3" = ~x <= -3, "5" = ~x >= 5)) + ..controls | user_id + ym, df)
iplot(list(m1, m2))

We can also double check that each user has data for each of the lags included above.

num_users <- n_distinct(df$user_id)
tt_counts <- df %>%
  filter(between(tt, -6, 5)) %>%
  group_by(tt) %>%
  count()
min_count <- min(tt_counts$n)
stopifnot(min_count == num_users)

It’s the binning of event study endpoints

Let’s start with no fixed effects. This is as expected. (Note that …)

m1 <- feols(dspend ~ i(tt) + ..controls, df)
m2 <- feols(dspend ~ i(tt) + ..controls, df)
iplot(list(m1, m2))

m1 <- feols(dspend ~ i(tt) + ..controls | ym, df)
m2 <- feols(dspend ~ i(tt) + ..controls | ym, df)
iplot(list(m1, m2))
